intro: Maharanga waddellii, commonly known as the Waddell's maharanga, is a rare and endemic plant species found in specific regions of New Zealand. It belongs to the Apiaceae family, characterized by its umbellate inflorescence and aromatic foliage. The plant typically grows in moist, shaded environments, often in forest understories. Its leaves are finely divided and have a distinctive, fern-like appearance. Due to its limited distribution and habitat specificity, it is considered a vulnerable species.
